# Slide 1

- Image SEGMENTATION
- Image segmentation is the process of partitioning a digital image into disjoined, meaningful regions. The meaningful regions may represent objects in an image of three-dimensional scene, regions corresponding to industrial, residential, agricultural, or natural terrain in an aerial recognizance application, and so on.

# Slide 4

- 1- Gray-Level Thresholding
- This technique is an example of the regional approach, which implies grouping pixels into distinct regions or objects. When using this technique for image segmentation, all pixels that have gray levels equal to or above a certain threshold are assigned to the object. The rest of the pixels are assigned to the object's background. If the image contains more than one object, then more threshold levels can be used to do the segmentation.

# Slide 8

- 2- Gradient-Based Segmentation
- This technique concentrates on the boundaries between different regions.  describes that are based on the gradient technique. They are the boundary tracking technique, the gradient image thresholding, and Laplacian edge detection. We describe each of these techniques briefly.

---
# Slide 9

- A- Boundary Tracking
- This technique starts with scanning the image for the pixel with the highest gradient. This pixel is for sure on the object's boundary. Then a 3-by-3 pixel segment (with the original pixel in its center) is used as tracking probe for the next pixel with the highest gradient, in the neighbor of the original one. This pixel is considered part of the object's boundary and the probe is moved to the new pixel to search for another boundary pixel. The process is repeated until a closed contour is formed. If, at any time, three adjacent pixels in the probe have the same highest gray level (i.e., gradient), the one in the middle is selected. If two have the same highest gradient, the choice is arbitrary.

---
# Slide 10

- B- Gradient Image Thresholding
- This technique is based on the following phenomenon. If we threshold a gradient image at moderate gray level, the object and the background stand below the threshold and most edge points stand above it . The technique works like this: We first threshold the image at a low level to identify the object and background, which are separated by bands of edge points. We then gradually increase the threshold level, causing both the object and background to grow. When they finally touch, without merging, the points of contact define the boundary .

# Slide 12

- Region-based segmentation
- Emphasis:
focus directly on detecting the regions
Common approaches:
– Region splitting
– Region merging
– Split-and-merge
– Region growing
May need a measure of uniformity for a given region (e.g., variance of intensity values)
May need a measure of similarity for 2 regions, or to
assess how well a particular pixel fits into a given region

---
# Slide 13

- Region splitting: high-level algorithm
- 1) Assign the entire image to a single region
2) Repeat until no changes occur
– Find the region that is the least uniform
– If the degree of uniformity is sufficiently bad,
subdivide this region into 2 (or more) new regions

---
# Slide 14

- Region merging: high-level algorithm 1 1
- 1) Assign every pixel in the image to a separate region
2) Repeat until no changes occur
– Find the 2 adjacent regions that are most similar
– If the degree of similarity is sufficiently good,
combine these regions to form 1 new region

---
# Slide 15

- Region merging: high-level algorithm 2
- 1) Find initial regions using some simple technique, such a
histogram-based thresholding followed by component
labeling
2) Repeat until no changes occur
– Find the 2 adjacent regions that are most similar
– If the degree of similarity is sufficiently good,
combine these regions to form 1 new region

---
# Slide 16

- Split-and-merge: high-level algorithm
- 1) Assign the entire image to a single region
2) Repeat until no changes occur
– Find the region that is least uniform
– If the degree of uniformity is sufficiently bad,
subdivide this region into 2 (or more) new regions
– Find the 2 adjacent regions that are most similar
– If the degree of similarity is sufficiently good,
combine these regions to form 1 new region

---
# Slide 17

- Region growing: high-level algorithm
- 1) Find “seed points” using some simple technique; each
of these points initially represents a region that will expand
2) Repeat until no changes occur
– Consider all unlabeled pixels that are neighbors of
existing regions, and identify the 1 pixel that is most
similar to a neighboring region
– If the degree of similarity is sufficiently good,
expand this region to contain the new pixel
3) Group any remaining pixels into “background”
region(s)

---
# Slide 18

- 3- Region Growing
- Region growing is one of the artificial intelligence techniques for digital image segmentation. This technique is especially useful in cases where prior knowledge of the scene features is not available. The technique works as follows: 
 the image is partitioned into many small regions. Then the properties of the pixels in each region are computed.
average properties of adjacent regions are examined. If the difference is significant, the boundary is considered strong and it is allowed to stay. Otherwise, the boundary is considered weak, and the two regions are merged. 
Step 2 is repeated until there are no more boundaries weak enough to allow regions merging.

# Slide 19

- Texture
- We can define texture as an attribute representing variations in brightness among the image pixels. This variation may be in the level of brightness, special frequencies, or orientation. 
Texture is sometimes seen as a measure of surface roughness. 
Some of the operators commonly used to detect texture in images are the rank operators, range operators, and gray-level variation. 
The rank operator measures the range between the maximum and minimum brightness values in the image. Larger range values correspond to surfaces with a larger roughness. 
The range operator converts the original image into one in which brightness represents texture . 
Gray-level variation can be measured by the sum of the squares of the differences between brightness of the center pixel and its neighbors. The root of resultant value is then calculated to give the root-mean square (rms) measurement of the surface roughness.

# Slide 20

- Edge Detection
- An edge in an image is a significant local change in the image intensity, usually associated with a discontinuity in either the image intensity or the the first derivative of the image intensity.
Type of edges
Step edge: where the image intensity abruptly changes from one value on one side of the discontinuity to a different value on the opposite side.
 Roof edge: where the image intensity abruptly changes value but then returns to the starting value within some short distance.

---
# Slide 21

- Steps in edge detection
- Filtering: to improve the performance of an edge detector with respect to noise.
Enhancement : to facilitate the detection of edges, it is essential to determine changes in intensity in the neighborhoodf of a point.
Detection: we only want points with strong edge content. However, many points in an image have a nonzero value for the gradient, and not all of these points are edges for a Chapter icular application. Thresholding provides the orientation used for detection.
Localization: the location of the edge can be estimated with subpixel resolution if required for the application.

- Characteristic of laplacian of gaussian
